==English==
===Etymology===
[[Category:Greek derivations]]
From Latinized Greek [[patheticus]], from [[Ancient Greek]] '''[[παθητικός]]''' {{italbrac|pathetikos}} “subject to feeling, capable of feeling, impassioned”, from '''[[παθητός]]''' {{italbrac|pathetos}} “one who has suffered, subject to suffering”, from '''[[παθείν]]''' {{italbrac|pathein}} “to receive an impression from without, to suffer”.

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɛtɪk|-ɛtɪk]]

===Adjective===
{{en-adj-more}}

# Arousing [[pity]], [[sympathy]], or [[compassion]].
#* ''The old man’s '''pathetic''' pleas for forgiveness stirred the young man’s heart.''
# Arousing [[scornful]] [[pity]] or [[contempt]], often due to miserable [[inadequacy]].
#* ''“You can't even run two miles?  That’s '''pathetic'''.”''

